Secure Boot is intentionally disabled on this host.

The Apple T2 chip performs its own boot verification before UEFI is
reached. The community workaround for running Linux on T2 requires
disabling the T2's own Secure Boot entirely — that removes the
hardware root of trust. Standard UEFI Secure Boot layered on top of
that path provides no meaningful protection because the T2's own
verification, which is the real trust anchor on this hardware, is
already off.

Layering UEFI SB on the T2 path also adds a failure mode: signature
mismatches during t2linux kernel upgrades, boot refusals after
firmware updates, additional debugging surface during an already
fraught T2-on-Linux experience. All cost, no benefit.

When T2 support matures and the T2's own Secure Boot can coexist
with Linux, re-evaluate this file.
